The '''A509''' is a short [[Roads in the United Kingdom#Classification|A-class]] road (around {{convert|30|mi}} long) for north-south journeys in south central [[England]], forming the route from [[Kettering]] in [[Northamptonshire]] to the [[M1 motorway|M1]] and [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5]] in [[Milton Keynes]]. 

From north to south, the road begins at [[Wicksteed Park]] in the outskirts of [[Kettering]]. It then crosses the [[A14 road (England)|A14]] (where it becomes a [[Roads in the United Kingdom#Classification|primary route]]) and goes through [[Isham]] and [[Great Harrowden]]. After this it goes on to form the [[Wellingborough]] western bypass before leaving [[Northamptonshire]] to cross into the [[Borough of Milton Keynes]] (ceremonial [[Buckinghamshire]]).  From there, it crosses the [[A428 road|A428]] at a roundabout and cuts through the centre of [[Olney, Buckinghamshire|Olney]]. South of Olney the road passes [[Emberton]], meeting the [[A422 road|A422]] just east of [[Newport Pagnell]], where the routes multiplex to form the Newport Pagnell eastern bypass. South of Newport Pagnell, the routes diverge at a roundabout with the A509 turning south and the A422 continuing westbound. Here the A509 is a single carriageway once more until it crosses the M1 at Junction 14, where it enters Milton Keynes proper and multiplexes for a short distance with the [[A4146 road|A4146]] (on separating, the latter takes over the 'primary route' designation and the A509 loses it).  Once more a dual carriageway, it runs for a further {{convert|4|mi}} past the edge of [[Central Milton Keynes]] (the [[central business district]]) and the [[Network Rail]] National Centre ('[[Quadrant:MK]]'), to link up finally with the [[A5 road (Great Britain)|A5]]. Through Milton Keynes the road is known as the H5 Portway.

==Incidents==
During 2005 there were two fatal crashes in the same {{convert|100|m|yd|abbr=on}} stretch of the road as it passes between [[Emberton]] and [[Petsoe End]].{{cn|date=June 2018}}  This area of the road had become notorious as a black spot for traffic accidents, and residents of Emberton had complained to [[Milton Keynes (borough)|Milton Keynes Borough Council]] for a number of years for improvements to the road.{{cn|date=June 2018}} In July 2005 local residents met in the village and demanded a {{Convert|40|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} speed limit and improvements.{{cn|date=June 2018}} These were promised by the Council within six months,{{cn|date=June 2018}} but were implemented in September 2006.{{cn|date=June 2018}}

