{{Infobox settlement <!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions --> | name = Martuni | native_name = Մարտունի | type = [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh|Province]] | image_map = NKR locator Martuni.png | seat_type = Capital | seat = [[Martuni (town)|Martuni]] | leader_title = Governor | leader_name = Nelson Soghomonyan | area_total_km2 = 951 | area_water_percent = Negligible | area_rank = [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh#By area|Ranked 6th]] | population_total = 24,300 <ref>http://stat-nkr.am/files/publications/2015/LXH_tverov_2015.pdf</ref> | population_as_of = 2015 | population_rank = [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh#By population|Ranked 2nd]] | population_density_km2 = auto | postal_code_type = [[Nagorno-Karabakh postal codes|Postal code]] | postal_code = | area_code_type = [[FIPS 10-4]] | area_code = | iso_code = | website = [http://gov.nkr.am/hy/regions/details/49/ Martuni Region] }} '''Martuni Province''' ({{lang-hy|Մարտունի}}) is a [[Administrative divisions of the Republic of Artsakh|province]] of the ''de facto'' [[Republic of Artsakh]]. The Republic has [[Political status of Nagorno-Karabakh|limited international recognition]]. It is ''de jure'' part of the Republic of [[Azerbaijan]]. The territory was formed from the Soviet-era [[raion]] of [[Martuni District (NKAO)|Martuni District]] within the former [[Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous Oblast]]. The eastern part of that District in under the [[de facto]] control of the Republic of [[Azerbaijan]]. The territory of the province is considered by Azerbaijan to be a ''de jure'' part of the wider district of [[Khojavend District|Khojavend]].
Martuni Province consists of the branch of the former Oblast which juts out farthest to the east, almost reaches [[Stepanakert]] on the west, and goes a little past [[Karmir Shuka]] on the south. The western half has many hills and small mountains, full of small villages, while the eastern half is very flat, with fewer villages, and the larger regional center of Martuni. Historically, this area was also known as ''Myus Haband'' and ''Varand''. Martuni Province has 35 rural communities and 1 urban community.
In 1991 the parliament of Azerbaijan, with the [[Law on Abolishment of Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous Oblast]], abolished Martuni District, incorporating its territory into the neighbouring [[Azerbaijan]]i [[Khojavend District]].
== Sites of interest == * [[Amaras Monastery]], one of the oldest monasteries in the former [[Kingdom of Armenia (antiquity)|Kingdom of Armenia]].
